This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.CL (Computation and Language) as it deals with language analysis and natural language processing (NLP) techniques to predict power relations in social interactions. It may also belong to cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) as it deals with analyzing social interactions and power dynamics. Additionally, it could be categorized under cs.SD (Sound and Music Computing) as it deals with analyzing the sound of language in social interactions. It may also belong to cs.LG (Machine Learning) as it presents a novel neural architecture for predicting power relations. Finally, it could be categorized under cs.CY (Computers and Society) as it deals with the social implications of language analysis and power dynamics.
